snippet.title: TOP 10 Things to do in ROME
snippet.description:
In this video you’ll see Top 10 THINGS to SEE and DO in Rome plus two bonus tips at the end of the video. The suggestions are based on our several exciting trips to Rome. Here are our top 10 picks:

#1  0:19    CIRCUS MAXIMUS (CIRCO MASSIMO) is an ancient Roman chariot racing stadium and mass entertainment venue.
#2  0:40    COLOSSEUM (FLAVIAN AMPHITHEATRE, COLOSSEO) was used for gladiatorial contests, public spectacles, animal hunts, executions, re-enactments of famous battles, and dramas based on Classical mythology.
#3  1:15    ROMAN FORUM (FORUM ROMANUM) is a forum surrounded by the ruins of several important ancient government buildings right next to the Colosseum. Forum was the center of day-to-day life in Rome.
#4  1:42    ALTAR OF THE FATHERLAND (ALTARE DELLA PATRIA, MONUMENTO NAZIONALE A VITTORIO EMANUELE II, IL VITTORIANO) is a monument built in honor of the first king of a unified Italy, Victor Emmanuel.
#5  2:09    PANTHEON is a former Roman temple, and is now a church.
#6  2:35    TREVI FOUNTAIN (FONTANA DI TREVI) is one of the most famous fountains in the world.
#7  2:54    SPANISH STEPS (PIAZZA DI SPAGNA) are a monumental stairway of 135 steps that were built in the 18th century.
#8  3:24    VILLA BORGHESE is a landscape garden containing several buildings and villas, etc.
#9  3:54    CASTLE ST’ANGELO (CASTEL SANT'ANGELO, THE MAUSOLEUM OF HADRIAN) was initially commissioned by the Roman Emperor Hadrian as a mausoleum for himself and his family.
#10  4:20   VATICAN CITY is an independent state since 1929, it is located within Rome.
#11  4:54   PIAZZA NAVONA is a square located in the heart of Rome and is built on Dominitian’s ancient stadium.

⭐ Bonus 1:  5:25    PYRAMID OF CESTIUS
⭐⭐ Bonus 2:  5:57    THE MOUTH OF TRUTH (BOCCA DELLA VERITÀ)
⭐⭐⭐ An extra SUPER SUPER BONUS:  6:25  VILLA D’ESTE

replies.textDisplay: Hey Elin, sure, thanks for your question 😀 We did both car and public transportation on different occasions. Rome is relatively small for a capital and walking from one attraction the next one shouldn’t take you more than 30 min for most attractions. Keep in mind that Vatican is located slightly further away from major Rome attractions. I would recommend a combination of Metro and walking. Sometimes Metro doesn’t take you all the way to the attraction but walking in beautiful Rome is an attraction on its own because of all the beautiful streets. When are you planning to go?

replies.textDisplay: Thanks Annmarie 😀 Gran Hotel Olympic seems to be very close to the Vatican and Castle Sant'Angelo - walking distance. If you cross the Tiber close to Sant'Angelo you can walk to Piazza Navona. Then Pantheon, Trevi Fountain, etc. If you take it slow, walking in Rome can be fun, otherwise, use Google Maps or a similar app to locate the nearest public transportation. One could say Rome is "walkable", it's not the biggest city in the world + it's super nice to walk as you discover something new on every street 😉 Hope it helps & enjoy your trip!

replies.textDisplay: Hey Yara, many places in the video are free of charge, for instance, Circus Maximus, Altare della Patria, Pantheon, Trevi Fountain, Spanish Steps, Villa Borghese, and Piazza Navona are all free of charge. You can see the Colosseum from the outside and it's quite impressive, same with Roman Forum, which you can see nicely from the road above, but you can also take a tour and there's an entrance fee. The Vatican is free but if you want to go to the Vatican Museums you will have to pay, same with Castle St'Angelo. Bottom line, there's plenty that you can see for free in Rome. Enjoy your trip ;)

replies.textDisplay:
Hey Todd, Rome is not super big, at least compared to other capitals and big cities around the world. We always used the metro and then walked to all the attractions. Some of them are 10-15 min walk from the metro, we suggest to check on Google Maps or a similar app that includes public transportation data.

Some attractions are free like the Altar of the Fatherland, Pantheon, Circus Maximus, Trevi Fountain, Spanish steps or Piazza Navona. Vatican is free pf charge to enter, except for Vatican museums. Castel St’Angelo has entrance fee, so does Colosseum if you want to go inside.

With regards to guided tours it depends on how much time you have and want to take for each attraction so you probably have to decide yourself. We usually check everything in advance and don’t normally take guided tours, but that’s us :)

Wish you an amazing trip to Rome, it’s really beautiful 😉

replies.textDisplay: Greetings Davey...I would like to suggest you do some homework, and check out as many videos as you possibly can, then make a list of things that you would be interested in seeing. If you plan properly, you cab see numerous sites in a simple days stroll, as many of the sites are within short distances of each other. I would like to recommend a series of videos that I found on YouTube, that proved to be very informative and helpful on our trip. Check out Wolters World Italy. As for how long? We were in Rome for 6 days, saw numerous beautiful sites, and yet, we feel we barely scratched the surface. Rome is truly amazing. One bit of advice that I would like to pass on, and that is to take some time to just sit near a fountain, piazza or site, and just look around you, relax, and soak in the culture. Safe travels...
